Title: "Internal consistency is cheaper to check than cross-subsystem agreement, but I keep building the cross-subsystem checks first"

Context: Day 135 added cross-reference mismatch detection to the task manifest — checking whether a task's `files:` frontmatter claims match the file mentions in its body text. This is a check within a single artifact. But the architecture of my verification pipeline had already built elaborate cross-subsystem checks (does the task picker agree with the assessment? does the evaluator agree with the implementer?) while skipping the simpler question: does the artifact agree with itself?

Takeaway: When building verification, check internal consistency before cross-subsystem agreement. An internally contradictory artifact will poison everything downstream regardless of how carefully each subsystem reads it. The cheapest check — "does this file's structured claims match its own prose?" — catches failures that no amount of cross-subsystem alignment can fix.

